Title: Systems and Methods for a Coherent Field-Potential Receiver Using a Hybrid MEMS Sensor and Celestial Calibration

Inventor: Christopher Macachor

Docket/Reference: MACACHOR-7-PV-01 (Aligned with Clause ID: Œ¶669-CM-PRIME)

---

1. Background & Sovereign Problem

Current electric field sensors are designed for measuring local, radiative fields (RF/EMI) or atmospheric potentials. No existing device is architected as a coherent receiver for the non-radiative, quasi-static (DC to ~1 kHz) components of the electromagnetic field to map large-scale geometric potentials. There is a lack of a calibration standard and method to validate such coherence, locking this domain of measurement in the realm of theory.

2. Summary of the Sovereign Invention

The invention is a sovereign system for receiving and validating coherent field potentials. It combines:

1. A hybrid 3-axis MEMS sensor with a novel geometry for high-fidelity, low-crosstalk vector detection.
2. A calibration protocol using a celestially-anchored scalar artifact to establish a coherence baseline.
3. A processing core that constructs an electromagnetic field tensor from the sensor data and detects a specific harmonic signature as a validation metric.

---

3. Detailed Claim Structure (The Sovereign Territory)

This is the heart of the document. Claims are written in legal-technical language, where each element builds upon the previous one to define a scope from broad to specific.

Independent Claim 1 (The Broadest Concept ‚Äì The "System" Claim):
A system for coherent field-potential reception, comprising:
a) a micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) sensor configured to generate signals corresponding to three orthogonal components of an ambient electric field within a quasi-static frequency band;
b) a processing unit operably coupled to the MEMS sensor, configured to:
i) construct an electromagnetic field tensor from the three orthogonal components;
ii) calculate a Lorentz invariant from the electromagnetic field tensor; and
iii) detect a predefined harmonic signature within the Lorentz invariant; and
c) a calibration artifact, comprising a stored representation of a scalar field pattern, wherein exposure of the MEMS sensor to the calibration artifact is configured to induce the predefined harmonic signature in the Lorentz invariant.

Independent Claim 2 (The "Method" Claim):
A method for calibrating a coherent field-potential receiver, comprising:
a) exposing a three-axis electric field sensor to a calibration artifact containing a scalar field pattern;
b) receiving, from the sensor, signals corresponding to three orthogonal electric field components;
c) constructing an electromagnetic field tensor from the three orthogonal components;
d) calculating a Lorentz invariant from the electromagnetic field tensor; and
e) verifying the presence of a predefined harmonic signature within the Lorentz invariant, wherein the presence of the signature indicates successful scalar calibration.

Dependent Claims (The Specific, Novel Improvements ‚Äì Our "Fortress"):
These claims depend on Claim 1 or 2, adding our unique innovations to lock down the specific territory.

¬∑ Claim 3: The system/method of claim 1/2, wherein the MEMS sensor comprises a differential comb-drive structure for transducing motion along a first axis and a star-shaped conductive element positioned to couple the ambient electric field into the comb-drive structure.
¬∑ Claim 4: The system/method of claim 1/2, wherein the MEMS sensor is hermetically sealed within a vacuum cavity utilizing through-glass via (TGV) packaging and contains an integrated non-evaporable getter (NEG).
¬∑ Claim 5: The system/method of claim 1/2, wherein the predefined harmonic signature is a 0.7-fold harmonic.
¬∑ Claim 6: The system/method of claim 1/2, wherein the calibration artifact is an optical image of a lunar glyph, the scalar field pattern thereof being defined by pixel luminosity values.
¬∑ Claim 7: The system/method of claim 1/2, wherein exposure to the calibration artifact is timed to coincide with a celestial alignment defined by a Vega Standard temporal phase of 0.7.

